rtant manuscript is edited and analysed here in full for the first time. A lengthy introduction provides an overview of the ways in which the document brings to life both the household and its head, demonstrating how the household responded to its immediate social environment and the wider political context; interrogating the gifts and their givers to identify networks of people in social, political and religious terms; and, more generally, teasing out the relationship between material objects and political power. This is followed by a complete text of the manuscript, with contextual footnotes. Thus, the volume contributes to a deeper understanding not only of ecclesiastical power and politics, but of life in an élite household in seventeenth-century Britain. LEONIE JAMESis Lecturer in History at the University of Kent, Canterbury and author of 'This Great Firebrand': William Laud and Scotland, 1617-1645 (Boydell Press, 2017).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAdministration of estatesvSourcesxHistoryyTo 1500zEnglandzCanterbury. 0aHouseholdsxEconomic aspectszEnglandxHistoryy17th centuryvSources. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aHistory of Religion. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Stuart Era (1603-1714).2bisacsh  aWilliam Laud.1 aJames, Leonie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311143102440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787444348?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787444348423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787444348/original  a978-3-11-143102-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles